# /usr/infrastructure/power_grids/
# The nervous system of civilization.
# Without electricity, /usr/ collapses to /bin/ within weeks.
#
# Global electricity generation: ~29,000 TWh/year (2023)
# Sources: coal (35%), gas (22%), hydro (15%), nuclear (10%),
#          wind (8%), solar (5%), other (5%)
#
# The grid is the largest machine ever built.
# It operates in real time — generation must match demand
# every second, or frequency deviates, equipment fails, blackouts cascade.
#
# Frequency: 50 Hz (most of world) or 60 Hz (Americas, parts of Asia)
# Tolerance: ±0.5 Hz. Beyond that: automatic load shedding.
#
# The 2003 Northeast blackout: one software bug in Ohio →
# 55 million people without power → $6 billion in damages.
# Cascading failure. One node → the whole network.
# See also: /bin/ecology_manager/food_web.net (keystone removal)
#
# Energy transition challenge:
# Renewables are intermittent (sun doesn't always shine, wind doesn't always blow).
# Grid-scale storage is the missing /lib/ — the shared library
# that makes intermittent sources reliable.
# Battery technology is the bottleneck.
# The physics is /lib/periodic_table.db — lithium, cobalt, nickel.
# The geopolitics is /usr/governance/ — who controls the mines.
